    <item>
      <title>SOAP and Perl</title>
      <link>https://theweeklychallenge.org/blog/soap-and-perl/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 22 Jun 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://theweeklychallenge.org/blog/soap-and-perl/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h4 id=&#34;disclaimer-image-is-generated-using-chatgpt&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;DISCLAIMER:&lt;/strong&gt; Image is generated using &lt;code&gt;ChatGPT&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/h4&gt;&#xA;&lt;hr&gt;&#xA;&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The current web software development space is dominated by &lt;code&gt;REST&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code&gt;GraphQL&lt;/code&gt;, and &lt;code&gt;gRPC&lt;/code&gt;. I have written about each of them recently.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;GraphQL&lt;/code&gt;: | &lt;a href=&#34;https://theweeklychallenge.org/blog/mojo-meets-graphql&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mojo meets GraphQL&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt; | &lt;a href=&#34;https://theweeklychallenge.org/blog/dbic-graphql&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;DBIx::Class and GraphQL&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt; | &lt;a href=&#34;https://theweeklychallenge.org/blog/cpan-graphql&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;CPAN and GraphQL&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt; | &lt;a href=&#34;https://theweeklychallenge.org/blog/mutation-in-graphql&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mutation in GraphQL&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt; |&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;code&gt;gRPC&lt;/code&gt;: | &lt;a href=&#34;https://theweeklychallenge.org/blog/rest-vs-grpc&#34;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;REST vs gRPC&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt; |&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;But there was one standard that was there before the others; &lt;code&gt;SOAP (Simple Object Access Protocol)&lt;/code&gt; which was created in the late &lt;code&gt;1990s&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;At that time, &lt;code&gt;SOAP&lt;/code&gt; was adopted as an industry standard by the &lt;code&gt;W3C (World Wide Web Consortium)&lt;/code&gt; and is still used today as the primary protocol for developing enterprise applications, used in large-scale distributed systems, secure financial transactions and secure communications.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
